Ans 1.1.2

  • From a passengers’ perspective, arrival delay is more important because departure delay only accounts for the delay while at the origin city whereas arrival delay accounts for the delay leaving from origin city, delay while in air, time spent rerouting, and/or time made up while in air.

Ans 1.1.3.b

  • Though ExpressJet has a median arrival delay of -7 minutes and US Airways has a median arrival delay of -6 minutes, we cannot say that ExpressJet is a more reliable airline because we don’t know the full distribution of each airlines’ arrival delay. It’s possible that ExpressJet has about half its flights that leave earlier than 7 minutes and then the other half that leave an hour late in comparison to US Airways, which might have a more even distribution.

assess_arr_delay <-

Ans 1.1.5.

  • The two days that are extreme outliers are:

    • February 8, 2013

    • February 9, 2013

  • It is possible that these two days were blizzard days that made it difficult for flights to take off or land in the New York area. The backlog of flights from the first day probably then rolled over to the second day as carriers tried to reschedule or reroute passengers.

flights <-
  flights %>%
  group_by(month, day) %>%
  mutate(
    num_flights = n(),
    cancelled = ifelse(is.na(arr_time), 1, 0),
    num_cancelled = sum(cancelled == 1),
    prop_cancelled = (num_cancelled / num_flights),
    dates = paste(month.abb[month], day, sep = "-")
  )

ggplot(flights) +
  geom_bar(aes(
    x = dates,
    y = (num_cancelled / num_flights)
  ),
  stat = "identity"
  ) +
  labs(
    x = "Dates",
    y = "Proportion Cancelled"
  )

# Recognizing that the outliers fall in February, we filter to zoom in to Feb.
ggplot(flights %>% filter(month == 2)) +
  geom_bar(aes(
    x = dates,
    y = (num_cancelled / num_flights)
  ),
  stat = "identity"
  ) +
  labs(
    x = "Dates",
    y = "Proportion Cancelled"
  ) +
  coord_flip()

not_cancelled %>%
  arrange(tailnum, time_hour) %>%
  group_by(tailnum) %>%
  mutate(delay_more_than1hr = dep_delay > 60) %>%
  mutate(Before_firstdelay = cumsum(delay_more_than1hr)) %>%
  filter(Before_firstdelay < 1) %>%

1.3.1 EDA: Exploring variation

Ans1.3.1.1a Overall pattern suggests, there are less diamonds that are expensive, more quantity of diamonds are available that are cheaper. Histogram of diamonds$price is skewed to right / positive. yes it fits the expectation as more buyers will be for low cost diamonds than expensive ones. Another explanation is that expensive diamonds must be rare so less quantity available.

print(summary(diamonds$price))
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     326     950    2401    3933    5324   18823
ggplot(data = diamonds, aes(price)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Ans1.3.1.1.b. Yes, there is a surprising thing in the diamonds data. Diamonds are less availablecompared to other values for price around $1400. We see a white gap when bins were increased or binwidth was reduced.

ggplot(data = diamonds, aes(diamonds$price)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 5000)

Ans1.3.1.2a. Data is skewed to right. Yes, it fits our expectations that less diamonds are available for (carats > 2). So the count for higher prices was lower.
Also as they are less in market or availability they are expensive.

print(summary(diamonds$carat))

ggplot(data = diamonds, aes(diamonds$carat)) +

Ans1.3.1.2b. There are 23 diamonds that are .99 carats and 1558 diamonds that are 1 carat. This may be because it is easier to sell something that is a round number like 1 (as opposed to .99) because more is better for the consumer. In the consumer’s mind, moving from a <1 carat to a 1 carat diamond is like moving into another level.

diamonds %>%
  filter(carat == 1 | carat == .99) %>%
  group_by(carat) %>%
  summarise(n())
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   carat `n()`
##   <dbl> <int>
## 1  0.99    23
## 2  1     1558

Ans1.3.1.3 Using coord_cartesian() and its xlim/ylim arguments changes x and y axis limits by zooming into the plot and does not change the underlying data. If we were to just use xlim and ylim, if observations are not in this range, they will be dropped.

Binwidth is how wide the bins are. If we leave binwidth on default, it attempts to calculate bin width by taking the range of the values in our variable and divide it by the default bins = 30. Setting binwidth overrides bins. It is best for the researcher to set binwidth that will allow for best viewing.

ggplot(data = diamonds, aes(price)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(2000, 5000))
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(data = diamonds, aes(price)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  xlim(2000, 5000)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

1.3.2 1.3.2 EDA: Navigating NAs

Ans1.3.2.1 Missing values are omitted when constructing a histogram, which is created to represent continuous variables. By default, missing values (NAs) are removed with a warning. If we include na.rm=TRUE, missing values are silently removed. Bar charts are created for categorical values and recognizes strings such as “NA”. Thus, all the NAs are “counted” and considered its own category.

Ans1.3.2.2 In mean() and sum(), na.rm=TRUE strips missing values before starting to calculate the mean and the sum.

2.2 Choose a month

Ans 2.1.1 Average arrival delays into either Chicago ORD or MDW are the lowest during the first quarter (especially at the end of January and parts of February), in early Spring (end of March/early April), around Thanksgiving week and in the early summer (May). Days in which at least 80% of flights are on time typically fall in the winter (Jan/Feb), early Spring (end of March/early April), early summer (May), and around end of November.

chi.flights.delay <- 
  chi.flights %>%
  filter(DEST == "ORD" | DEST == "MDW") %>%
  group_by(FL_DATE) %>%
  summarise(AVG_DELAY_BY_DAY = mean(ARR_DELAY, na.rm = TRUE),
            TOTAL_FL_BY_DAY = n(),
            AVG_DAY_OF_WEEK = mean(DAY_OF_WEEK, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  arrange(AVG_DELAY_BY_DAY
  )

ONTIME_FL_BY_DAY <- chi.flights %>%
  filter(DEST == "ORD" | DEST == "MDW") %>%
  group_by(FL_DATE) %>%
  mutate(ON_TIME = ifelse(ARR_DELAY <= 0, 1, 0)) %>%
  filter(ON_TIME == 1) %>%
  summarise(ON_TIME = n()
  )

chi.flights.delay$ON_TIME <- ONTIME_FL_BY_DAY$ON_TIME

chi.flights.delay <- 
  chi.flights.delay %>%
  mutate(PROP_ON_TIME = ON_TIME / TOTAL_FL_BY_DAY,
         PROP_ON_TIME_80 = PROP_ON_TIME >= .8)

print(chi.flights.delay)

Ans 2.1.3.c

  1. Weather Dataset

    • Because weather, specifically precitation levels in Chicago, tends to also impact flight arrival and delay times, we should also analyze weather patterns. Given average precitation levels for specific days of the year, we can determine whether there is a high likelihood of rain or other weather elements that will impact arrival of flights. Source: https://w2.weather.gov/climate/local_data.php?wfo=lot

  2. Traffic Dataset

    • Another factor to take into account when planning a large scale event may be traffic. Analyzing data for the last few years to find dates/times in which traffic congestion is highest may be helpful. That being said, perhaps it may also be helpful to compile data for major events happening in the area including athletic/sports games, concerts, races, and conferences that may increase traffic. Source: https://data.cityofchicago.org/ Transportation/Chicago-Traffic-Tracker-Historical-Congestion-Esti/77hq-huss

2.3 Pick an airline

Ans 2.2.1 If the convention were to be during the period of April 5-April 15, we would recommend F9 (Frontier Airlines) for timeliness.

avg_delay_carrier <-
  chi.flights %>%
  group_by(FL_DATE, OP_UNIQUE_CARRIER) %>%
  summarise(AVG_DELAY_CARRIER = mean(ARR_DELAY, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  filter(FL_DATE >= "2016-04-05" & FL_DATE <= "2016-04-15")

ggplot(avg_delay_carrier) +

  )

2.4 Reconsider the date?

Ans 2.3.1 Because the date we chose falls during hurricane season and because Greer, South Carolina typically is in the path of hurricanes, we may want to reconsider rescheduling the conference to early April. It is a safer bet to have the most important people at the convention arrive on time.
